   <font class="ArticleSource"><big>Upcoming Chat:</big></font>
   <font class="ArticleHead"><big>They stole this one from me!</big></font>
   <font class="ArticleAuthorLight">&nbsp;filed by </font><font class="ArticleAuthor">Coray</font>
   <div align="right">
   <font class="ArticleTime">11/19/2003 01:03 PM CST &nbsp;&nbsp; 65 Comments</font>
   <div align="left">
   <font class="ArticleText">Absor posted the time for the upcoming chat next Monday that will deal with the melee changes, and along with that, he posted some actual specifics of what it's all going to entail.<p><h1><font size="4">EverQuest Chat on November 24th at 6:00pm - 7:00pm pacific time. Melee System Enhancements!</font></h1><p><strong>You've been asking for them and now we're ready to discuss them. We're taking a big departure from what many of you are used to when it comes to combat. With that in mind, here is a brief summary of these exciting enhancements to better help you target your questions to us during the live chat. Don't worry if you miss the chat, we'll post the logs on EverQuestLive.com </strong><p><ul><br>    <li><strong>Increase the contributions melee classes provide in a group setting </strong></li><br>    <li><strong>Address the current deficit between the pure melee classes and other classes </strong></li><br>    <li><strong>Add more depth and potential for skilled play to melee combat </strong></li><br>    <li><strong>Provide a system that encourages attentiveness and decision-making skills, without focusing heavily on twitch gameplay</strong></li><br></ul><p><strong>Take advantage of an opponent's weakness. See an opening, strike home for the kill! </strong><p><strong>Monks, Rogues and Warriors will gain the ability to recognize certain weaknesses in an opponent's defense. These &quot;Openings&quot; will be a variety of types and can occur based on several different situations during combat. Be quick though, an opening will not present itself for long. Strike quick with a new combat skill once your character recognizes an opening. These new combat skills are being designed just for this combat system revision. Using and maintaining these skills expends the character's Endurance (a new statistic, calculated from the character's basic stats). </strong><p><strong><i>Here's a combat example:</i></strong><p><strong>A warrior is serving as the tank for his group, standing in front of a goblin. While battling the goblin, the warrior makes an exceptional parry and is presented with an opening. An indicator appears with the &quot;opening icon&quot; and the word &quot;Parry&quot; next to it (this information also appears in the chat window). </strong><p><strong>Now is his opportunity to strike back after the exceptional parry! Only certain combat skills can be used to react to a parry opening. Other types of openings will allow the use of other skills. Some skills may be usable in response to more than one type of opening. Also, your position in relation to the target can change the effectiveness of certain skills. </strong><p><strong>In this case, our warrior knows that he can use one of three combat skills, each having some merit. One might stun the target, one might increase the hate generated by the warrior for a few rounds, and one might make it easier for everyone to hit the NPC.</strong><p><strong>In this case, our warrior elects to try to stun the goblin. He presses the appropriate button and luck smiles upon him as he successfully executes the strike, leaving the goblin standing dumbly for a combat round. </strong><p><strong>Increasing Your Endurance and Learning New Skills </strong><p><ul><br>    <li><strong>Increase Endurance by increasing attributes or by acquiring special items that directly increase your Endurance pool </strong></li><br>    <li><strong>Find tomes or instructions manuals and take them to specific trainers to learn new skills </strong></li><br>    <li><strong>Choose your skills from skill categories (such as Tactical) containing skills focused to a purpose </strong></li><br>    <li><strong>Most openings are available only to a single character, but some are available to all nearby characters </strong></li><br>    <li><strong>Disciplines will be transferred to this new system </strong></li><br>    <li><strong>Existing Discipline timers will be reviewed, and several will probably be set to their own timer </strong></li><br>    <li><strong>Disciplines will require an Endurance cost </strong></li><br>    <li><strong>Hybrids will receive a limited Endurance pool for their disciplines</strong></li><br></ul><p><strong>There will be other changes as well. Keep your eyes on the Test server and our update messages for more details as we move forward. </strong><p><strong>This new system is much more flexible than the existing disciplines. It will be relatively easy to add new combat skills, as well as new skills that are not limited to openings. This system creates the possibility for tremendous enhancement in the future, allowing groups a large number of options when it comes to melee combat. </strong><p>Before I even touch any of that I'm going to go over a few things that have irritated me as far as peoples reactions go. First of all, a common thing I've seen is that some other game has something similar. If people actually had ever played many roleplaying games, you'd know that the vast majority of them have something atleast in the same neighborhood as this. I have never played Daoc, or Wow, and my own suggestion was in this ballpark.<p>Next, you have the people who complain that they are pure melee and shouldn't have to press buttons or have special combat moves. Again about all I can say is that EQ was fairly unique in how you could just AFK during combat, and I mean unique in a bad way. <p>Now to address the changes themselves. Again, to the whiners, I have never played daoc and I don't have a clue how it does things, so just keep your mouths shut. Anyways, it's an interesting approach and a good one for a multi-player game, IF in fact it meets my expectations or exceeds them.<p>One of my first thoughts was that it would be similar to playing that game where you whack a mole or crocodile as they come out of the machine, but this line helped a bit...<p><strong>Provide a system that encourages attentiveness and decision-making skills, without focusing heavily on twitch gameplay</strong><p>The next interesting bit was the ability for a skill to affect things for everyone attacking a creature..<p><strong>...one might make it easier for everyone to hit the NPC.</strong><p>Which is great, because it obviously boosts the entire group in that situation.<p>Now, some thoughts on skills and endurance...<p><strong>Increase Endurance by increasing attributes or by acquiring special items that directly increase your Endurance pool </strong><p>It would be great here if pure melee could get atleast some credit for the +mana gear we end up getting. I have +1500 in mana gear, and there are people who have even more than that, it would be good for us to get atleast some bonus from that.<p><strong>Find tomes or instructions manuals and take them to specific trainers to learn new skills </strong><p>This is another point people have complained about, that they'll have to farm and trade or whatever for new skills, much like casters have to do with spells. I would say first of all, that it's not quite the same so it shouldn't be treated the same by Sony. Caster spells are more important to them, than melee skill tomes will probably be to melee, so tomes shouldn't all be as common as caster spells are.<p>This subject of tomes and learning skills is a critical one because on one hand, you want to put a lot of skills out there, the common ones for the balance changes to matter. The average joe doing an experience group, needs to have some skills for any of this to mean anything.<p>But then there should be a lot that have to be worked for and that are rare. I'm not talking about just adding a few books to Quarm, there should be ones throughout pop, and of course the next expansion.<p>My only final thoughts on all of this, is that I hope that they don't go through and alter current encounters because of this. Somehow I doubt that any particular opening or skill is going to make much of a difference. A few percentage points more dps from a person or group, or less dps from a mob, are not really big deals. <p>Also, ideally this would just be a piece of the puzzle, and they allude to that...<p><strong>...as well as new skills that are not limited to openings.</strong><p>and...<p><strong>There will be other changes as well.</strong><p>But they don't talk a lot about any other changes that are less interesting such as mitigation or hitpoint adjustments, so hopefully either more information on specific skills comes up, on the defensive side of things, or information about other changes comes up in the chat.<p>As far as immediate player reactions, they tend to be mixed as I noted above with a lot of people acting like idiots, in particular atleast half of the <a href="http://www.thesteelwarrior.org/forum/showthread.php?s=&amp;threadid=4420" target="_new">warriors</a>. Rogues <a href="http://pub146.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showMessageRange?topicID=29015.topic&amp;start=1&amp;stop=20" target="_new">seem</a> to be a bit more patient, or perhaps it's that they realize that they aren't <em>that</em> broken. The <a href="http://pub147.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm1.showMessage?topicID=42463.topic" target="_new">monks</a>, aside from the stupid 'Oh it's just like game x!' where they list 7 different games as being what Sony is stealing this idea from, start out atleast lukewarm, but then it quickly descends with few intelligent people, making few intelligent comments.<p>Everyone can have their own opinion of what has been said by Sony about it, but it's pretty pointless to draw too many conclusions yet, since it's not so much the overall system that matters, but the actual skills that they put in it and how it all works when we get our hands on it that will determine if it rocks or sucks.</font>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>
